<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN"> 
<HTML> 
  <HEAD>
    <title>julian_time</title>
    <script type="text/javascript">	
    </script>
  </HEAD>
  <body link=#bbeeff" vlink="#ffffff" alink="#FF0000" style="background-color: #000000; color: #aaddff">
    <a href="http://equationoftime.herokuapp.com">Home</a>
    <% if @solar %>
    <h1>The Astronomical Julian Period Day Number(ajd) = </br>
        Julian Period Day Number(jd) - 0.5 = midnight the day before.</h1>  
        The time reference we need starts at midnight UTC the day before.</br>
        Normally we use just Julian Period Day Number (Midday)</br>
        for calculations like Sunrise and Sunset.</br>
        Astronomers use Julian Period Day Number (Midday) for logging of astronomical observations</br>
        as this would be the start and end of a nightly session.
    <p>
      <h2>These terms are calculated with the Universal Time Coordinate<br />
          or GMT of the current time.</h2>
    </p>
    <p>
      <% today = @solar.ajd + 0.5 %>
      <input style="font-weight: bold" value="&nbsp;&nbsp;<%= today.to_s %>"/> : Julian Period Day Number today at noon.
    </p>  
    <p>
      <h1>class Date, method ajd()</h1> or
      <h2>today = @solar.ajd(t = Time.now.utc)</h2>
      <% today = @solar.ajd %>
      <input style="font-weight: bold" value="&nbsp;&nbsp;<%= today.to_s %>"/> : Astronomical Julian Period Day Number is previous midnight.
    </p>
    <p>
      <h1>class Time, methods now() and utc</h1> or
      <h2>now = @solar.julian_day_fraction_time_now(t = Time.now.utc)</h2>
      <% now = @solar.julian_day_fraction_time_now %>
      <input style="font-weight: bold" value="&nbsp;&nbsp;<%= now.to_s %>"/> : Day fraction of Julian Period Day Number is hours decimal / 24.
    </p>
    <p>
      <h1>Combined</h1> or
      <h2>today + now</h2>
      <input style="font-weight: bold" value="&nbsp;&nbsp;<%= (today + now).to_s %>"/> : Astronomical Julian Period Day Number + julian day fraction.<br /> This is the calculated value passed as a parameter to the julian_century_time calculation method.<br />
       see: Julian Century Time
    </p>  
    <% end %>
  </body>
</HTML>
